==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trill
<hw>Trill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trillen</ets> to roll, turn round; of Scand. origin; cf. Sw.
<ets>trilla</ets> to roll, Dan. <ets>trilde</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧yrla</ets> to whirl, and E. <ets>thrill</ets>. Cf.
<er>Thrill</er>.]</ety> <def>To flow in a small stream, or in drops
rapidly succeeding each other; to trickle.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now and then an ample tear <qex>trilled</qex> down⟦br⟧
Her delicate cheek.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whispered sounds⟦br⟧
Of waters, <qex>trilling</qex> from the riven stone.</q>
<rj><qau>Glover.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trill
<hw>Trill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trillen</ets>; cf. Sw. <ets>trilla</ets> to roll.]</ety> <def>To
turn round; to twirl.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Gascoigne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bid him descend and <qex>trill</qex> another pin.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trill
<hw>Trill</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trilled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trilling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[It. <ets>trillare</ets>;
probably of imitative origin.]</ety> <def>To impart the quality of a
trill to; to utter as, or with, a trill; <as>as, to <ex>trill</ex> the
<it>r</it>; to <ex>trill</ex> a note.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sober-suited songstress <qex>trills</qex> her lay.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Trill
<hw>Trill</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To utter trills or a trill; to
play or sing in tremulous vibrations of sound; to have a trembling
sound; to quaver.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To judge of <qex>trilling</qex> notes and tripping feet.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Trill
<hw>Trill</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>trillo</ets>, fr.
<ets>trillare</ets>. See <er>Trill</er> to shake.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sound, of consonantal character, made with a rapid
succession of partial or entire intermissions, by the vibration of some
one part of the organs in the mouth -- tongue, uvula, epiglottis, or lip
-- against another part; <as>as, the <ex>r</ex> is a <ex>trill</ex> in
most languages</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The action of the organs in producing such sounds;
<as>as, to give a <ex>trill</ex> to the tongue</as>. d</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A shake or quaver of the voice in
singing, or of the sound of an instrument, produced by the rapid
alternation of two contiguous tones of the scale; <as>as, to give a
<ex>trill</ex> on the high C</as>. See <er>Shake</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trillachan</ent>⟦br⟧
